# Agents

## How Agency binding works in Cursor

Agency specialist rules live in `.cursor/rules/agency-*.mdc`. Cursor does **not** have a `subagent_type` parameter — the equivalent mechanism is **including `@agency-<slug>.mdc` in the task prompt** sent to each implementation agent. That reference causes Cursor to load the full specialist rule (persona, constraints, anti-patterns, deliverable templates) into the agent's context.

**Critical:** Agency Cursor slugs come from each agent's frontmatter `name:` field, slugified — **not** from the upstream filename. So `engineering-backend-architect.md` → `agency-backend-architect.mdc`. Do **not** use division-prefixed Cursor names like `@agency-engineering-backend-architect.mdc` — they do not exist.

## Superpowers override (non-negotiable)

`.claude/skills/subagent-driven-development/implementer-prompt.md` shows `Task tool (general-purpose)`. In Cursor this means dispatch a new agent session with no specialist attached. **You MUST instead prepend the matching `@agency-<slug>.mdc` reference** at the top of every implementation task prompt you send. The Superpowers body (task text, context, self-review protocol, status reporting) still applies in full — only the persona binding is added.

Example of correct task prompt structure:

```
@agency-backend-architect.mdc

You are implementing Task N: [task name]

## Task Description
[FULL TEXT of task from plan...]

## Context
[scene-setting: where this fits, dependencies, architectural context]

[... rest of Superpowers implementer-prompt.md template ...]
```

Without the `@agency-*.mdc` line, the agent has no specialist constraints and produces generic output. The `@` reference is what loads the 200+ lines of persona — it is not cosmetic.

## Dispatch rules

- **EVERY implementation task prompt** must start with the matching `@agency-<slug>.mdc` reference
- **Superpowers reviewer subagents** (spec-compliance, code-quality) keep their Superpowers role — do **not** prepend Agency rules to those
- **Plan is silent on roles?** Map tasks using `.ai/agents.md` before dispatching — then prepend the resolved rule
- **Missing rule?** If the `@agency-*.mdc` file is not present in `.cursor/rules/`, run `npx ai-dev-setup init --vendor-only --force` to regenerate. Do not proceed without it

## Common role → Cursor rule map

> See `.ai/agents.md` for the full reference. Cursor slugs differ from Claude Code filenames.

| Task focus | Cursor rule |
|------------|-------------|
| API / backend / server logic | `@agency-backend-architect.mdc` |
| UI / frontend / components | `@agency-frontend-developer.mdc` |
| Tests / API testing | `@agency-api-tester.mdc` |
| Performance / benchmarking | `@agency-performance-benchmarker.mdc` |
| Infra / CI / scripts | `@agency-devops-automator.mdc` |
| System architecture | `@agency-software-architect.mdc` |
| Senior generalist dev | `@agency-senior-developer.mdc` |
| Code review | `@agency-code-reviewer.mdc` |
| Security review | `@agency-security-engineer.mdc` |
| Documentation | `@agency-technical-writer.mdc` |
| Product / requirements | `@agency-product-manager.mdc` |

## Docs to load before implementing

Before the specialist begins any task, load the docs that apply to the work. Do not start writing code without reading the relevant doc first.

| Work type | Must read before starting |
|-----------|--------------------------|
| Creating or editing any `src/` file | `docs/CONVENTIONS.md` — layer rules, naming, directory placement |
| API/HTTP routes, controllers, services | `docs/API-PATTERNS.md` — validation contract, layer boundaries |
| Error handling or logging | `docs/ERROR-HANDLING.md` |
| Auth, secrets, or user-input handling | `docs/SECURITY.md` |
| Tests | `docs/TESTING-STRATEGY.md` |
| Architectural or cross-module change | `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` |

## Anti-patterns

- Sending a task prompt with only "You are operating as Backend Architect — ..." invented inline. That 1-line description is not the agent file — the full file has critical rules, deliverable templates, and quality standards.
- Using Claude Code filenames (`engineering-backend-architect`) in Cursor `@` references — those files are not in `.cursor/rules/`.
- Skipping Agency binding for "quick" tasks. Quality enforcement is in the agent file; skipping it consistently produces the quality degradation that Agency was installed to prevent.
- One `@agency-*.mdc` at the top of a multi-task session used as a catch-all. Each dispatched task prompt must carry its own binding.
